}}'''''Romances''''' is the fifteenth [[studio album]] by Mexican singer [[Luis Miguel]], released on August 12, 1997, by [[Warner Music Latina]]. It is the third album of the ''Romance'' series, in which Miguel covers Latin songs from 1940 to 1978. Aside from Miguel, the production also involved [[music arranger|arranger]] [[Bebu Silvetti]], and [[Armando Manzanero]], who directed all of Miguel's ''Romance'' albums. ''Romances'' consists of twelve [[cover version]]s and two new compositions by Manzanero and Silvetti. Recording took place in early 1997 at the Ocean Way recording studio in Los Angeles, California.

''Romances'' has sold over 4.5&nbsp;million copies and received platinum certifications in several Latin American countries, the United States and Spain. Miguel promoted the album by touring the United States, Latin America and Spain. The album was generally well-received by critics, who praised Miguel's vocals as well as the song selection. The album earned Miguel several awards, including a [[Grammy Award]] in the United States. Six singles were released: "[[Por Debajo de la Mesa]]", "El Reloj", "Contigo (Estar Contigo)", "De Quererte Asi (De T'Avoir Aimee)", "[[B<U+00E9>same Mucho]]", and "Sabor a Mi".

== Background ==
In 1991 Miguel released ''[[Romance (Luis Miguel album)|Romance]]'', a collection of classic Latin ballads, the oldest of which dates back to the 1940s. The album was [[music producer|produced]] by Armando Manzanero and arranged by Bebu Silvetti,<ref name="romance">{{cite web|title=Romance&nbsp;<U+2014> Credits|url=http://allmusic.com/album/romance-r100917/credits|accessdate=2011-04-01|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> and was credited for revitalizing the [[bolero]] genre.<ref name="popculture"/> It also made history as the first Spanish-language album to be certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in the United States.<ref name="latinoise">{{cite web
|title= Luis Miguel
|url=http://www.latinoise.com/Luis_Miguel.html
|publisher=Latinoise
|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref> A follow-up to ''Romance'' was released in 1994 under the title ''[[Segundo Romance]]'' (''Second Romance''), which was produced by Miguel, Juan Carlos Calder<U+00F3>n and Kiko Cibrian.<ref name="segundoromance">{{cite web|title=Segundo Romance&nbsp;<U+2014> Credits|url=http://allmusic.com/album/segundo-romance-r203611|accessdate=2011-04-01|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> Both albums received a platinum certification by the RIAA in the United States and also became successful in countries outside of Latin America and the United States, such as [[Finland]] and [[Saudi Arabia]],<ref name="growsup"/> selling over twelve million copies combined.<ref name="growsup">{{cite web
| last = Obejas
| first = Achy
| date = 1996-08-30
|title= Luis Miguel Grows Up And Moves On With His Latest Albums
|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-08-30/entertainment/9608300302_1_luis-miguel-nada-es-igual-aries
|work=Chicago Tribune
|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]
|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref>{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Luis Miguel|accessdate=2011-02-19}}<ref>{{cite journal|year= 1997|journal= [[Forbes]]|volume= 160|issue=5<U+2013>9 |page=155|last=La Franco|first= Robert|publisher= Forbes Inc.}}</ref>

In December 1996 Miguel held a press conference in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], where he announced his desire to record a third ''Romance'' album and mentioned the possibility of working with Manzanero and [[Juan Gabriel]]. He also expressed an interest in singing in Italian and Portuguese,<ref>{{cite news |title=Va por el tercero|newspaper=[[Reforma]]|url=http://busquedas.gruporeforma.com/reforma/Pages/BuscaImpresa.aspx|publisher=[[Grupo Reforma]]|trans_title=Going for third|date= 1996-12-10|language=Spanish|accessdate=2011-04-09}}{{subscription required}}</ref> although the album's songs are originally all in Spanish. Two months later Manzanero confirmed that he was working with Miguel on another bolero-inspired ballads album, under the tentative title ''Tercer Romance'' ("Third Romance").<ref name="feb1997">
{{cite journal
| last = Lannert
| first = John
| date = 1997-02-08
| title = Latin Notas
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 109
| issue = 6
| page = 32
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=wA4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA31&dq=%22luis%20miguel%22%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-03-28}}</ref> Miguel's record label confirmed that fourteen tracks would be included on the album under the title ''Romances''.<ref>{{cite news |title= Es Luis Miguel un clasico del romance|first=Ang<U+00E9>lica |last= De Le<U+00F3>n|newspaper=Reforma|url=http://busquedas.gruporeforma.com/reforma/Pages/BuscaImpresa.aspx|publisher=Grupo Reforma|trans_title=Is Luis Miguel romantic classic|date= 1997-07-16|language=Spanish|accessdate=2011-03-28}}{{subscription required}}</ref>

== Recording and production ==
[[File:Luismiguel9900.jpg|thumb|[[Luis Miguel]] worked with Armando Manzanero and Bebu Silvetti on the recording of ''Romances''.|alt=A man is smiling to the right.]]
Miguel collaborated with Silvetti for the arrangement of ''Romances'', while Manzanero was in charge of direction.<ref name="Jenkins"/>  Recording began on March 18, 1997,<ref>{{cite news |title= Confirma 'Romance III'|url=http://busquedas.gruporeforma.com/reforma/Pages/BuscaImpresa.aspx|deadurl=yes|newspaper=Reforma|publisher=Grupo Reforma|trans_title='Romance III' confirmed|date= 1997-01-16|language=Spanish|accessdate=2011-04-09}}{{subscription required}}</ref> at [[Ocean Way Recording]] in [[Hollywood]] and at [[The Hit Factory]] in New York City.<ref name="Liner"/> During the recording of ''Romances'', as in ''Romance'', Silvetti employed his signature style of arrangements known as the "Silvetti Sound", which Leila Cobo of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' describes as "anchored in sweeping melodies, lush string arrangements, acoustic instrumentation, and above all, unabashed [[romanticism]]."<ref name="dec2001">
{{cite journal
| last = Cobo
| first = Leila
| date = 2001-12-29
| title = Source of 'Silvetti Sound' Still Excels
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 113
| issue = 52
| page = 15
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=sBIEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA15&dq=bebu%20silvetti%20luis%20miguel%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-04-03}}</ref> Silvetti has stated that when he produces an album he does not simply copy his own arrangements, because he feels that would be "ridiculous", and prefers to be creative within his own style.<ref name="dec2001"/> About the selection of songs for the album, Manzanero stated that "I give [Miguel] the songs, and he chooses what he wants to record."<ref name="may2003">
{{cite journal
| last = Cobo
| first = Leila
| date = 2003-05-10
| title = Armando Manzanero
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 118
| issue = 19
| page = 36
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=qg0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA36&dq=%22romances%22+%22luis+miguel%22+intitle:billboard#v=onepage&q&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-04-03}}</ref> Participants in the recording sessions included sixty-one musicians from the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Garay|first=Adriana|date=1997-05-28|title=<U+00A1>Espectacular!|url=http://busquedas.gruporeforma.com/reforma/Pages/BuscaImpresa.aspx|language=Spanish|newspaper=Reforma|publisher=Grupo Reforma|trans_title= Spectacular!|accessdate=2011-06-15}}{{subscription required}}</ref>

Miguel covers twelve Latin ballads in ''Romances'', including songs by [[Jos<U+00E9> Antonio Mendez]], [[Carlos Arturo Briz]], [[Consuelo Vel<U+00E1>zquez]] [[<U+00C1>lvaro Carrillo]], [[Roberto Cantoral]], [[Mar<U+00ED>a Grever]], [[Enrique Santos Discepolo]], [[Agust<U+00ED>n Lara]], and [[Luiz Bonf<U+00E1>]].<ref name="romance"/><ref name="segundoromance"/> The latter composer wrote the song "Manha do carnavel" ("Morning of Carnival") in Portuguese, later translated into Spanish by Jesus Maria Arozamena Bersategui as "Cancion de Orfeo" ("Orpheus's Song").<ref>{{cite web
|title=Manha de Carnaval&nbsp;<U+2014>Luiz Bonf<U+00E1>
|url=http://allmusic.com/song/manha-de-carnaval-t1156328
|work=''Allmusic''
|publisher=Rovi Corporation
|accessdate= 2011-03-14}}</ref> "De Quererte Asi" ("If I Love You Like This") is a French song, originally performed and written by [[Charles Aznavour]], which was translated into Spanish by Alex Marcoriginates.<ref>{{cite web
|title=De T' Avoir Aim<U+00E9>e&nbsp;<U+2014>Charles Aznavour
|url=http://allmusic.com/song/de-t-avoir-aime-t3230181
|work=''Allmusic''
|publisher=Rovi Corporation
|accessdate= 2011-03-14}}</ref>  Miguel had covered some of the aforementioned composer's songs on his previous ''Romance'' albums.  Miguel covers Manazero's songs "Voy a Apagar la Luz/Contigo Aprendi" ("I Am Going To Turn Off The Lights/With You I Learned") and "Amanecer" ("To Be Awake").<ref name="Romances"/> The two original compositions were "Por Debajo de la Mesa" ("Underneath the Table") by Manzanero and "Contigo (Estar Contigo)" ("To Be With You") by Bebu Silvetti and Sylvia Riera Iba<U+00F1>ez.<ref name="Romances"/>

== Commercial reception ==

=== Album ===
The album was released on August 12, 1997, in the United States and, by the week of August 23, 1997, it debuted at number two on the [[Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Latin Albums &nbsp;<U+2014> Week of August 23, 1997 |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-albums?chartDate=1997-08-23 |accessdate=2011-02-19|date=1997-08-23 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> A week later it became number one, which it has been for a total of eleven non-consecutive weeks. ''Romances'' was even more successful in the [[Latin Pop Albums|''Billboard'' Latin Pop Albums]] chart, having been number one for 13 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Pop Albums &nbsp;<U+2014> Week of August 23, 1997 |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/latin-pop-albums?chartDate=1997-08-23 |accessdate=2011-02-19|date=1997-08-23 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> On the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart it peaked at number fourteen, with sales of over 57,000 units within the first week<ref name="aug1997">
{{cite journal
| last = Lannert
| first = John
| date = 1997-08-30
| title = Latin Notas: Chart Notes
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 109
| issue = 35
| page = 33
| url =http://books.google.com/books?id=_gkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA33&dq=%22romances%22+%22luis+miguel%22+intitle:billboard#v=onepage&q=%22romances%22%20%22luis%20miguel%22%20intitle%3Abillboard&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-06-15}}</ref><U+2014>a record at that time for a Spanish-language album.<ref name="latinoise"/> It was also Miguel's highest-peaking album in the ''Billboard 200'' until the release of ''[[Complices]]'' in 2008, which peaked at number ten.<ref>{{cite web|title=Compilices&nbsp;<U+2014> Luis Miguel |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/luis-miguel/complices/1137334 |accessdate=2011-02-19|date=2008-05-24 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> It was the second best-selling Latin album in the United States during 1997, after ''[[Tango (Julio Iglesias album)|Tango]]'' by [[Julio Iglesias]].<ref>{{cite journal
|title=The Year In 1997
|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0g0EAAAAMBAJ&dq=intitle%3Abillboard&q=luis+miguel+romances#v=onepage&q&f=false
|volume=109
|issue=52
|page=57
|work=Billboard
|publisher=Prometheus Global Media
|date=1997-12-27
|accessdate=2011-07-06}}</ref> By October 1997 it had sold over a million copies in Mexico and was certified quadruple platinum in the country, as well as across Central America.<ref>
{{cite journal
| last = Lannert
| first = John
| date = 1997-10-18
| title = Latin Notas
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume= 109
| issue = 42
| page = 44
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=nAkEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billboard+review+romances+%22luis+miguel%22&q=%22romances%22#v=onepage&q&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-02-19}}</ref><ref name="laprensa"/> A year after release it received a platinum certification in the United States by the RIAA.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|title=Romances|artist=Luis Miguel|type=album|accessdate=2011-02-19}} In Argentina it reached number one on the [[CAPIF]] albums chart and was the best-selling album of 1997 in the country, with sales of approximately 781,000 copies.<ref name="capif">
