|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-10-03/entertainment/9710030393_1_armando-manzanero-songs-oldies
|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]
|publisher=Tribune Company
|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref>
| rev3 = ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]''
| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name="daily">{{cite web
| last =  Valdespino
| first = Anne
|title=Sound Check
|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/SOUND+CHECK.-a083877338
|date=1997-08-29
|work=Los Angeles Daily News
|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]
|accessdate=2011-02-19
}}</ref>
}}

''Romances'' was generally well received by critics, who praised Miguel's [[tenor]] voice and the album's selection of songs. Terry Jenkins of [[Allmusic]] praised the collaborative work of Silvetti and Manzanero and called ''Romances'' "a sensuous, enchanting album".<ref name="Jenkins"/> [[Achy Obejas]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called Miguel's voice the album's strong point and noted the "presence of electronic instruments and the darker, more somber mood".<ref name="Obejas"/> On the other hand, she felt that Miguel was beginning "to slip", citing the tracks "Jurame" and "Por Debajo de la Mesa" as examples. Anne Valdespino of the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' praised the selection of songs and Miguel's performance, calling the performer a "class act".<ref name="daily"/>

At the [[40th Grammy Awards]], Miguel received the award for [[Best Latin Pop Performance]].<ref>{{cite web
|title=The 1998 Grammy Award Winners
|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE1DD103EF935A15751C0A96E958260
|date=1998-02-26
|work=[[The New York Times]] publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]
|accessdate=2011-02-19
}}</ref> Miguel also received a [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|Billboard Latin Music Award]] for "Male Pop Album of the Year" and a [[World Music Awards|World Music Award]] for "Best Selling Latin Artist".<ref name="popculture">{{cite book
| first1 = Cordelia 
| last1 = Candelaria
| first2 = Peter 
| last2 = Garcia
| first3 = Arturo 
| last3 =Adalma
| volume = 2
| title = Encyclopedia of Latino popular culture
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=3uD6PKXl3q4C&lpg=PA552&dq=%22world%20music%22%20awards%20%22luis%20miguel%22%20%22romances%22&pg=PA551#v=onepage&q&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-03-14
| year = 2004
| publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group
| location = Westport, United States
| isbn = 9780313322150
| pages = 551<U+2013>552
}}</ref><ref>
{{cite journal
| last = Lannert
| first = John
| date = 1998-04-28
| title = Latin Music Award Winners, Include First Timers, Familiar Faces
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 110
| issue = 15
| page = 74
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=rg4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=latin+conference+intitle:billboard#v=onepage&q&f=false
}}</ref>
Miguel received a Premio Amigo and Premio Onda for "Best Latin Singer of the Year" in Spain,<ref name="latinoise"/> and the album was nominated for a Premio Amigo for "Best Latin Album".<ref>{{cite web
|title=La Revista: Gentes
|url=http://www.elmundo.es/magazine/num109/textos/gente2.html
|date=1997-11-16
|language=Spanish
|work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]
|publisher=[[Unidad Editorial|Unidad Editorial, S.A.]]
|accessdate=2011-02-26
}}</ref> Armando Manzanero received a [[Broadcast Music Incorporated]] award for his work on "Por Debajo de la Mesa".<ref>{{cite web
|title=BMI Latin Awards: 1999
|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/533568
|date=1999-01-01
|publisher=Broadcast Music Incorporated
|accessdate=2011-02-19
}}</ref>

== Legacy ==
{{Main|Todos Los Romances|Mis Romances}}

Warner Music released a three-disc [[compilation album]] titled ''[[Todos Los Romances]]'' ("All The Romances") in 1998, which contains all the tracks from Miguel's ''Romance'' albums.<ref>{{cite web|title=Todos Los Romances&nbsp;<U+2014> Luis Miguel|url=http://allmusic.com/album/todos-los-romances-r368169|accessdate=2011-04-02|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> The album peaked at number twelve in the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart and at number six in the ''Billboard'' Latin Pop Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Todos Los Romances&nbsp;<U+2014> Luis Miguel |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/luis-miguel/todos-los-romances/315860 |accessdate=2011-04-02|date=1998-09-19 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> It was certified gold in Argentina.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Argentina|artist=Luis Miguel|accessdate=2011-04-02}} In 2001 Miguel released a fourth album, covering Latin ballads, titled ''[[Mis Romances]]'' ("My Romances").<ref>{{cite web|title=Mis Romances&nbsp;<U+2014> Luis Miguel|url=http://allmusic.com/album/mis-romances-r561574|accessdate=2011-04-02|work=''Allmusic''|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> The album peaked at number 115 in the ''Billboard'' 200, number two in the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums, number five in Spain, and number one in the ''Billboard'' Latin Pop Albums in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mis Romances&nbsp;<U+2014> Luis Miguel |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/album/luis-miguel/mis-romances/505988 |accessdate=2011-04-02|date=2001-12-08 |work=Billboard |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref><ref>
{{cite journal
| date = 2002-02-09
| title = Hits of the World
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 114
| issue = 6
| page = 45
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=_w8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA73&dq=%22luis%20miguel%22%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=PA45
| accessdate = 2011-04-02}}</ref><ref>
{{cite journal
| date = 2002-01-12
| title = Hits of the World
| journal = Billboard
| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.
| volume = 114
| issue = 2
| page = 43
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=9Q8EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA34&vq=%22luis%20miguel%22&dq=%22luis%20miguel%22%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false
| accessdate = 2011-04-02}}</ref> It was certified gold in Brazil, double platinum in Argentina, and quadruple platinum in the United States (Latin field) and Mexico.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Luis Miguel}}{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Argentina|artist=Luis Miguel|accessdate=2011-04-02}}{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Brazil|artist=Luis Miguel|accessdate=2011-04-02}}{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Mexico|artist=Luis Miguel|accessdate=2011-04-02}}

